theorem
((x0 in ( dom f ) & f is_continuous_in x0) implies (||. f .|| is_continuous_in x0 & ( - f ) is_continuous_in x0))
proof
assume A1: x0 in ( dom f );
assume A2: f is_continuous_in x0;
A3: x0 in ( dom ||. f .|| ) by A1,NORMSP_0:def 3;
now
let s1;
assume that
A4: ( rng s1 ) c= ( dom ||. f .|| )
and
A5: (s1 is  convergent & ( lim s1 ) = x0);
A6: ( rng s1 ) c= ( dom f ) by A4,NORMSP_0:def 3;
then A7: ( f /. x0 ) = ( lim ( f /* s1 ) ) by A2,A5,CKB6:def 1;
A8: ( f /* s1 ) is  convergent by A2,A5,A6,CKB6:def 1;
then ||. ( f /* s1 ) .|| is  convergent by NORMSP_1:23;
hence ( ||. f .|| /* s1 ) is  convergent by A6,CKB5:1;
thus ( ||. f .|| . x0 ) = ||. ( f /. x0 ) .|| by A3,NORMSP_0:def 3
.= ( lim ||. ( f /* s1 ) .|| ) by A8,A7,LOPBAN_1:20
.= ( lim ( ||. f .|| /* s1 ) ) by A6,CKB5:1;
end;
hence ||. f .|| is_continuous_in x0 by FCONT_1:def 1;
( ( - 1 ) (#) f ) is_continuous_in x0 by A2,CKB14:1;
hence thesis by VFUNCT_1:23;
end;
